07992nam a22011295i 9783110734157DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107341577 a10.1515/97831107341572doi  a(DE-B1597)575678  a(OCoLC)1376931200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPE1315.M6bD46 202304a425.6223/eng/202304241 aDepraetere, Ilse, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModels of Modals :bFrom Pragmatics and Corpus Linguistics to Machine Learning /cIlse Depraetere, Bert Cappelle, Martin Hilpert, Pascal Denis, Mathieu Dehouck, Susanne Flach, Natalia Grabar, Cyril Grandin, Clemens Hufeld, Benoît Leclercq, Hans-Jörg Schmid, Thierry Hamon, Ludovic De Cuypere. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VI, 274 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTopics in English Linguistics [TiEL] ,x1434-3452 ;v11000tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 English modals: An outline of their forms, meanings and uses -- t2 Modality revisited: Combining insights from Construction Grammar and Relevance Theory -- t3 Possibility modals: Which conditions make them possible? -- t4 Necessity modals and the role of source as a predictive factor -- t5 You must/have to choose: Experimenting with choices between near-synonymous modals -- t6 Does the intersubjectivity of modal verbs boost inter-individual differences? -- t7 Modals as a predictive factor for L2 proficiency level -- t8 Revisiting modal sense classification with contextual word embeddings -- t9 Modals in the network model of Construction Grammar -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModal verbs in English communicate delicate shades of meaning, there being a large range of verbs both on the necessity side (must, have to, should, ought to, need, need to) and the possibility side (can, may, could, might, be able to). They therefore constitute excellent test ground to apply and compare different methodologies that can lay bare the factors that drive the speaker’s choice of modal verb. This book is not merely concerned with a purely grammatical description of the use of modal verbs, but aims at advancing our understanding of lexical and grammatical units in general and of linguistic methodologies to explore these. It thus involves a genuine effort to compare, assess and combine a variety of approaches. It complements the leading descriptive qualitative work on modal verbs by testing a diverse range of quantitative methods, while not ignoring qualitative issues pertaining to the semantics-pragmatics interface. Starting from a critical assessment of what constitutes the meaning of modal verbs, different types of empirical studies (usage-based, data-driven and experimental), drawing considerably on the same data sets, shows how method triangulation can contribute to an enhanced understanding. Due attention is also given to individual variation as well as the degree to which modals can predict L2 proficiency level.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish languagexModality. 0aEnglish languagexVerb. 0aLinguistics. 4aCorpuslinguistik. 4aModalverben. 4aPragmatik.  aEnglish Modals, Pragmatics, Corpus Linguistics, Machine Learning.1 aCappelle, Bert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCappelle, Bert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Cuypere, Ludovic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDehouck, Mathieu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDehouck, Mathieu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1